I don't know if that's true or not, but that's how it feels to me.Maybe it's also because of the way it's used. It's full of people who seem to be constantly competing for attention, and it's difficult to have meaningful conversations with anyone in that kind of environment. I don't feel like I'm getting anything out of it, and that's why I just stay away.Maybe it's also because of the amount of time it takes. It seems like I'm always playing catch-up with the conversations, and that's not something I'm willing to do. I'd rather spend my free time doing something else.At the end of the day, I just don't use Discord. It's not something that fits my personal preferences, and that's why I stay away. Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.

>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

I have a small meditation-type exercise to share that might be useful to have as a daily goal. It's called the "5-senses" exercise, and it's about being mindful. Note, being mindful is about being self-aware, but not self-centered or self-conscious (a subtle difference, but important).
Basically, you just sit quietly, wherever you may be, and go through each of your sense.
What can you see around you? Describe it to yourself using specific words. Is the wall beige or tan? Is it roughly finished, smooth, or scratched? Are the leaves of the trees more green or yellow? Is the wind blowing them around, or is the air still? And so on
What can you feel? Are your clothes heavy or light? Is there sunlight shining on your skin, do you feel its warmth? Or maybe you can feel the gentle breeze of a fan or air conditioner brushing your hair.
What can you hear? Are there dogs barking in the distance? Maybe the sound of traffic or the wind through the trees.
What can you smell? Maybe your clothes smell faintly of your laundry detergent. Or maybe you can smell some coffee or tea from your mug. If you're outside, you can probably smell all sorts of plants or the exhaust from a car that passed by.
What can you taste? What did you eat last? Are you chewing gum? Has it lost its flavor, or is it still pleasing to your tongue? Maybe you can taste the air slightly if you breath in.

Hopefully, the end, you'll feel a bit calmer. I have found it useful for clearing my head of unwanted thoughts that stubbornly refuse to leave. It helps distract my brain with more immediate things and makes it easier for me to move on afterwards.

Echoing what the other anons have said. A job that takes up 40+ hour per week is as much (if not more) of a time sink than many full time students would have with a typical classload. It's good to set goals for yourself so you have a way to measure progress and adjust your plan accordingly, but make sure to give yourself some leeway so that you can work with your existing responsibilities.

>>29274402
>on the weekends i really should be dumping 5-6 hours into it, but instead i zone out until afternoon and start late
That's a lot of time to dedicate to do anything, and placing this pressure on yourself to meet such a high expectation makes success seem like a foregone conclusion. Let me offer a different approach: try building up to a more lengthy study period by first establishing shorter study times. These could be very short study times, mind you. You might start with just studying for 10 or 15 minutes in the evenings, then work up slowly from there. The next evening might be 17 minutes, then 20, then 25, and so on. The idea is to make this goal achievable and repeatable so that it can become a fixture of your routine. Then increasing the time and rigor will come more naturally.

>if i don't get my shit together there's literally no point in doing anything at all with my life
Careful with this all-or-nothing mindset. No one's "got their shit together" because there is always something in life to be improved upon. It's just like trying to clean an entire house, you never really finish because something else inevitably gets dirty. Cleaning a house is a process rather than a single action. It's the same with life.

Lastly, you've been working so hard, be proud of that! We're all rooting for you, anon

posts.com:
>>29273969
Taking extra T to boost your T probably won't have the effects you desire beyond the short term. Spare T metabolises into E2, and E2 shuts down your T production. What will happen is you get a week or two of high T, which fades into slightly high T and elevated E, which then fades back to your normal T levels as your body stabilises around the steroids you're taking. You'd basically have to ramp up and replace your natural production entirely with supplemental T, and then you're still going to end up with elevated E (which is why steroid users grow boobs).

Your natural T production isn't determined by how much T there is in your blood, they're determined by how much E2 there is in your blood. Leftover T turns into E2. If you have a naturally low T level, that means your androgen receptors just aren't using more T than that, because enough T is left over to tell your testicles to ramp down. Barring things like damage to the testicles or hypothyroidism I don't know anything about, your blood will probably have as much T as your body needs.

I recommend you not play with steroids, and just get your body in shape with discipline and hard work. A good exercise regime will not only stabilise your circadian rhythm, making it easier to sleep properly, but it will also increase your body's androgen receptiveness, boosting how much T you can make use of, and thus also boosting how much T your body will produce. It'll also produce a lot of serotonin, which is basically a "feel good" hormone.

>>29280697
It's anecdotal. Might be true, might not be. Basically, when you swallow E2, either as a whole pill or as part of your saliva if you're doing sublingual, it will go through your liver and metabolise into estrone, which some think plays a role in cis puberty breast development.

Plenty of trannies who have done E2 monotherapy from day one and grown big tits too, so it's dubious there's a benefit. Powers suggests that oral E can help "reboot" stalled breast development, but that's still anecdotal.

Valerate is better than straight E2, but enanthate is better than valerate. It's about half lives. Enanthate has twice the half life valerate does, which means it's way less spiky. Valerate is usually one injection per week, and the curve for that is as bad as enanthate once every other week. I recommend enanthate weekly, you get a smooth curve, which means no risk of PMS.

>>29281362
The esters of estradiol aren’t active drugs in your body. They have estrogenic effects because your body metabolizes them into bioidentical estradiol, the exact same as what’s produced naturally. The only thing different esters can change is how long that metabolism takes to happen, which is why they have different half lives.

Noun, denoting the ability of a person to be regarded as a member of an identity group or category, such as racial identity, ethnicity, caste, social class, sexual orientation, gender, religion, age and/or disability status, that is often different from their own.[1][2][3][4] Passing may be used to increase social acceptance[1][2] in order to cope with stigma by removing stigma from the presented self and could result in other social benefits as well. Thus, passing may serve as a form of self-preservation or self-protection in instances where expressing one's true or prior identity may be dangerous.[4][5] Passing may require acceptance into a community and may also lead to temporary or permanent leave from another community to which an individual previously belonged. Thus, passing can result in separation from one's original self, family, friends, or previous living experiences.[6] While successful passing may contribute to economic security, safety, and avoidance of stigma, it may take an emotional toll as a result of denial of one's previous identity and may lead to depression or self-loathing.[4] When an individual deliberately attempts to 'pass' as a member of an identity group, they may actively engage in performance of behaviors they believe to be associated with membership of that group. Passing practices can also include information management where the passer attempts to control or conceal any stigmatizing information that may reveal disparity from their presumed identity.[7]

Etymologically, the term is simply the nominalisation of the verb pass in its phrasal use with for or as, as in a counterfeit passing for the genuine article or an impostor passing as another person. It has been in popular use since at least the late 1920s.[8][9][10][11]

>>29276625
So the supposed depression from mdma is kind of a meme and typically results from a few preventable things:
1. Impure product (mdma cut with amphetamines or piperazines are typically the biggest culprit). It's pretty obvious you've had stuff that's been cut if it's hard to go to sleep after or the high lasts more than 4 or 5 hours after your last dose (molly's timeframe is super consistent). Always test your drugs kids
2. You do it way too often (give yourself at least a month between rolls) or you do way too much in a night continually trying to keep the high going into the next day. Often times people that do too much also don't care where their stuff comes from so they're not getting pure stuff and the problems compound
3. You don't take care of yourself before, during, or after the trip. Eat well on the day of, fruits and veggies and healthy carbs, don't eat too much meat esp red meats in the few hours before. Drink tons of water during and after and avoid things like alcohol. Take a multivitamin and 5htp after you've come down before you go to bed.
Molly is always a bit draining and you'll usually feel a little groggy the next day but if you follow this advice you'll find that you actually have an afterglow or even an anti-depressant effect for up to a week or two after the experience. Safe travels friends :)

I'm not an expert on voice training at all, but I have a couple of ideas of things that might be causing that excessive brightness that is I assume the thing you're complaining about making your voice clocky.

1) Are you raising the middle and front of your tongue when moving into your speaking position? That can cause excessive brightness and nasality in the sound.

2) I've seen that some voice training guides use eeeeeee or "ehhhhh" unvoiced to teach you to shrink your resonant space, but I think that shape has a lot of horizontal spread and can make you super bright, I think taking an 'uuuuhhhhhhh" mouth shape up gives you a similar decrease in resonant space in the vocal tract while still allowing you to have a rounder sound. At least that's why I came to from trying both approaches.

3) If I were you I'd consider that voice good enough to start using in public right now, honestly. I can understand you aren't perfectly happy with it yet, but it's genuinely good enough that I don't think its worth continuing to speak in your default voice to avoid using it.
